RABIES - INDONESIA (06): (BALI) NUSA PENIDA
*******************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1]
Date: Tue 22 Feb 2011
Source: Malay Peninsula Standard (In Malayan, trans. by Bali Animal
Welfare Association, edited]


A 66-year-old male resident of Banjar Kalang Sari, Nusa Penida,
Klungkung died of rabies. The victim died after being treated at Nusa
Indah Ward, Sanglah Hospital. The victim was a referred patient from
Klungkung Hospital. Once he arrived at Sanglah Hospital on Saturday
(19 Feb 2011) at 16.45 WITA (Central Indonesian Time), he immediately
received intensive care treatment in the Nusa Indah Ward. The victim
finally died on Sunday (20 Feb 2011) at 22.00 WITA.

According to Dr IGB Ken Wirasandhi, the secretary of Rabies Control
Team at Sanglah Hospital the victim had dog bite history 3 months ago
on his right shinbone. And he didn't clean his wound. "The victim
already showed clinical symptoms such as hydrophobia, aerophobia,
hypersalivation, and agitation," said Ken when interviewed on Monday
(21 Feb 2011).

With regard to the death of a Songan village resident, who had died
as a result of rabies virus infection 2 years [after receiving a dog
bite], Dr Ken explained, that rabies is invariably fatal [when the
virus reaches the brain] and [he could not predict precisely] when the
virus would reach the brain. "The location of the bite and the numbers
of bites also determine the length of time taken for the virus to
reach the brain. Also the number of rabies virus particles transferred
by the bite was relevant.

From current data gathered, the number of casualties resulting from
bites by stray dogs on Nusa Penida was now 2. In total the number of
suspected cases of rabies virus infection [in Bali overall] was now
183. Of these 87 people had died [as result of confirmed] rabies virus
infection since 2008 until now [see comment below].

Communicated by:
Merritt Clifton
Editor, Animal People
